Part 1: Wrangling¶

Problem 1: Using SQL compute a relation containing the total payroll and winning percentage (number of wins / number of games * 100) for each team (that is, for each teamID and yearID combination).¶

In [102]:
# Python packages for (sqlite) data access and extraction
import sqlite3 as sql
import pandas as pd

# Read the sqlite file and establish a sql connection
sqlite_file = "lahman2014.sqlite"
conn = sql.connect(sqlite_file)

# Extract the desired columns from the Salaries table and store a new column with the sum of total payroll grouped by each team and year
salary_query = "SELECT teamID, yearID, sum(salary) as total_payroll FROM Salaries GROUP BY teamID, yearID"

# Read the salary_query into a pandas dataframe
team_salaries = pd.read_sql(salary_query, conn)

# Extract the desired columns from the Teams table and calculate the winning percentage grouped by each team and year and store it in a new column
winnings_query = "SELECT teamID, yearID, franchID as franchiseID, W as wins, G as games, (W/(G*1.0)*100) as winning_percentage FROM Teams GROUP BY teamID, yearID" 

# Read the winnings_query into a pandas dataframe
team_winnings = pd.read_sql(winnings_query, conn)

# Merge the two dataframes by left join on teamID and yearID on the Salaries table
salaries_winnings = pd.merge(team_salaries, team_winnings, on=["teamID", "yearID"]) 

# Visualization
salaries_winnings

Write-up for Part 1 Problem 1:¶

In this part, the goal is to use SQL compute a relation containing the total payroll and winning percentage (number of wins / number of games * 100) for each team based on the teamID and yearID. The intuition behind this is to first extract a data query of total payroll and winning percentage seprately from the Salaries table and Teams table (salary_query = "SELECT teamID, yearID, sum(salary) as total_payroll FROM Salaries GROUP BY teamID, yearID" [Note grouping by teamID and yearID allows the sum function of all players' salaries to calculate the total payroll of a team in a year]; winnings_query = "SELECT teamID, yearID, franchID as franchiseID, W as wins, G as games, (W/(G*1.0)*100) as winning_percentage FROM Teams GROUP BY teamID, yearID" [Note multiplying G by 1.0 is necessary for correct SQL integer and float division]). 

Then, we read the two queries into pandas dataframes (team_salaries = pd.read_sql(salary_query, conn); team_winnings = pd.read_sql(winnings_query, conn)) and join the two together to form the relation table by matching the teamID and yearID. When we look at the two tables from the sqlite, we notice there are more team entries in the Teams table which date further back to the 1800s. For those years, there is no salaries data available in the Salaries table. 

In order to address the missing data, pd.merge(team_salaries, team_winnings, on=["teamID", "yearID"]) allows us to perform a left inner join on the Salaries table so it extracts the data from the Teams table that match the Salaries table and discard the rest that are missing salaries.

Write-up for Part 2 Problem 2:¶

In this part, the goal is to plot the distribution of payrolls of the teams conditioned on time (from 1990 to 2014). In order to achieve that, we first need to extract the data we need for our graph, so I created a dataframe copy of the original one and dropped the unneeded columns and perserved only the rows within the year range. Then, I called groupby("teamID") on the dataframe to group the data by each team and make the visualization. 

The first graph is a line graph with all of the distributions of payrolls of teams over the years on the same plot. The second graph is subplots of a line graph of the distribution of payrolls for each team separately over the years.

Question 1: What statements can you make about the distribution of payrolls conditioned on time based on these plots?¶

If we take a look at each sub line graph, we can notice there are some missing data for some teams as their line graph is broken or shorter than the others. Therefore, we cannot conclude too much about the overall trending of the total payroll of teams. If we look at the line graph with all of the distributions of payrolls of teams together, we can observe that the average total payrolls have been increasing over the years from 1990 to 2014. Also, the spread of the data and variance have increased over the years from 1990 to 2014 as well since we can see that the differences of total_payrolls have become larger and larger among the teams.

Write-up for Part 2 Problem 4:¶

In this part, the goal is to break down the data set from 1990-2014 into five even time periods and create a scatter plot for each time period comparing the mean winning percentage vs. the mean payroll for each team.

My approach was to first extract a copy of the dataframe and drop the unneeded columns. Then, I used pd.cut(x=payroll_winning["yearID"], bins=[1989, 1994, 1999, 2004, 2009, 2014]) to bin the dataframe into five time periods based on the yearID. This allows us to group the dataframe by the binning time intervals and calculate the average payroll and average winning percentage accordingly. Lastly, we drop the rows with missing entries in our table and count the number of instances for each time period. 

Now, it is ready for plotting. We use the count of teams in each time period to break the dataframe into five separate dataframes based on the time period and generate a scatter plot separately for each one of them and label the points and draw the linear regression line.

Question 2: What can you say about team payrolls across these periods? Are there any teams that standout as being particularly good at paying for wins across these time periods? What can you say about the Oakland A's spending efficiency across these time periods¶

When we look at the five scatter plots of the average winning percentage vs. the average payroll of each time period, we can observe that on average, all the teams' payrolls have been increasing over the years. Also, the variances of the average payroll of teams have been increasing as well. 

Additionally, there is an obvious correlation between the average winning percentage and average payroll of teams. It seems that the teams with higher average payroll tend to have higher average winning percentage according to the linear regression lines for time periods after 1994. For example, from 2000-2014, NYA has the highest average payroll and the highest average winning percentage, and from 1995-1999, they have the second highest average winning percentage while having the highest average payroll, so they are particularly good at paying for wins over the time periods. 

On the opposite side, team Oakland A's spending efficiency is much better. From the scatter plots, we can observe that they are able to have a high average winning percentage with a low average payroll over the time periods (they were always above the linear regression line by a lot). For example, from 2000-2004, Oakland A had nearly the same amout of average winning percentage as NYA as the top of the MLB league while spending about 8*(10^7) less on average than NYA in that time period.

# Drop the unneeded columns from the dataframe (only want teamID, yearID, and total_payroll) 
std_payroll = salaries_winnings.drop(columns=["franchiseID", "wins", "games"])

# Calculate the sum of total_payroll for each year
sum_payroll = std_payroll.groupby("yearID")["total_payroll"].sum()

# Calculate the count of the total_payroll for each year 
count_payroll = std_payroll.groupby("yearID")["total_payroll"].count()

# Calculate the standard deviation of total_payroll for each year
std_per_year = std_payroll.groupby("yearID")["total_payroll"].std()

# Merge (sum_payroll / count_payroll) as a column of average payroll for each year and the std_payroll dataframe by left join on yearID
std_payroll = pd.merge(std_payroll, (sum_payroll / count_payroll), on=["yearID"]) 

# Merge std_per_year as a column of standard deviation of payroll for each year and the std_payroll dataframe by left join on yearID
std_payroll = pd.merge(std_payroll, std_per_year, on=["yearID"])

Write-up for Part 3 Problem 5:¶

In this part, the goal is to create a new column in our dataframe for the calculations of the standardized payroll of each team in each year from 1990-2014. In order to achieve this, I first created columns for calculations of the average payroll of each year and standard deviation of payroll of each year and left join them on the original dataframe copy. Then, I was able to calculate the standardized payroll by the formula (total_payroll - average payroll by year) / (standard deviation by year).

Problem 6: Repeat the same plots as Problem 4, but use this new standardized payroll variable.¶

In [112]:
# Python packages used for building the desired scatter plots 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from IPython import display

# Create a copy of the original std_payroll dataframe for plotting
std_payroll_scatter = std_payroll

# Store a new column of the binning intervals for five time periods from year 1990-2014                                                                   
std_payroll_scatter["year_bins"] = pd.cut(x=std_payroll_scatter["yearID"], bins=[1989, 1994, 1999, 2004, 2009, 2014])

# Calculate the average_winning_percentage and average_standardized_payroll for each team in each time period and store the values in a new dataframe
average_std_payroll = std_payroll_scatter.groupby(["year_bins", "teamID"])[["winning_percentage", "standardized_payroll"]].mean()

# Reset index for the average_std_payroll table
average_std_payroll = average_std_payroll.reset_index()

# Rename the column names of the dataframe for average_winning_percentage and average_standardized_payroll
average_std_payroll = average_std_payroll.rename(columns={"winning_percentage": "average_winning_percentage", "standardized_payroll": "average_standardized_payroll"})

# Drop the rows with missing entries
average_std_payroll = average_std_payroll.dropna()

# Count how many teams have data entries for each time period
team_count = average_std_payroll.groupby("year_bins").count()

# Visualization
display.display(average_std_payroll)
display.display(team_count)

Write-up for Part 3 Problem 6:¶

In this part, we use a similar approach as problem 4 to make our scatter plots for each of the five time periods. The only difference is that we are using average standardized payroll values in our plot instead of the average payrolls to compare with mean winning percentage.

Question 3: Discuss how the plots from Problem 4 and Problem 6 reflect the transformation you did on the payroll variable.¶

The scatter plots from problem 6 using the average standardized payroll instead of the average payroll are more organized and easier to analyze the correlation between the winning percentage and the payroll of a team. For example, there were overlapping points on the scatter plots without the standardized payroll, but that is more difficult to tell the difference of the correlations between the teams. In our scatter plots with the standardized payroll, the points are more spread out, so the correlation between the winning percentage and payroll is more obvious to tell.

#3. Spending efficiency¶

Problem 8: Create a new field to compute each team's spending effiency and make a line plot with year on the x-axis and efficiency on the y-axis.¶

In [119]:
# Create a copy of the dataframe
payroll_efficiency = std_payroll

# Using the calculated expected winning percentage to calculate efficiency with the formula and create a new field of spending efficiency in the dataframe
payroll_efficiency["efficiency"] = payroll_efficiency["winning_percentage"] - (50 + 2.5 * payroll_efficiency["standardized_payroll"])

# Extract the data with the desired set of teams only
payroll_efficiency = payroll_efficiency[payroll_efficiency["teamID"].apply(lambda x: x == "OAK" or x == "BOS" or x == "NYA" or x == "ATL" or x == "TBA")]

# Drop the unneeded columns for the plot
payroll_efficiency = payroll_efficiency.drop(columns={"total_payroll", "winning_percentage", "average_payroll", "std_by_year", "standardized_payroll", "year_bins"})

# Set the yearID as the index of the dataframe
payroll_efficiency = payroll_efficiency.set_index("yearID")

# Make the line plot for each team from 1990-2014 with efficiency on the y-axis and yearID on the x-axis
payroll_efficiency.groupby(["teamID"])["efficiency"].plot(xlabel="yearID", ylabel="efficiency", figsize=(16,12),
                                                          title="OAK, BOS, NYA, ATL, TBA's spending efficiency from 1990-2014", legend=True)
